</form><html xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xmlns:math="java.lang.Math" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" xmlns:xs="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema" xmlns:fo="http://www.w3.org/1999/XSL/Format" xmlns:fn="http://www.w3.org/2005/02/xpath-functions" xmlns:xdt="http://www.w3.org/2005/02/xpath-datatypes" xmlns:caml="http://lc.ca.gov/legalservices/schemas/caml.1#" xmlns:xhtml="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><head><title>AB2503:v98#DOCUMENT</title><meta name="dc:identifier" content="AB2503"/><meta name="dc:title" content="AB &#xA;              2503-&#xA;                AMENDED&#xA;              "/><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html;charset=utf-8"/></head><body><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Start</h2></span><div id="bill_all" align="justify"><div id="about"><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><table style="border-collapse: collapse" cellSpacing="0" align="center" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td align="center"><span style=" text-transform: uppercase; font-size: 1em">
                Amended
               IN </span><span style=" text-transform: uppercase; font-size: 1em">
                Assembly
              </span> <span style="text-transform: uppercase">April 13, 2026</span><br/></td></tr></tbody><tbody><tr><td align="center"/></tr></tbody></table></div><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><font size="3" style="FONT-FAMILY: MinionPC, Arial Unicode MS">
                    CALIFORNIA LEGISLATURE—
                    2025–2026 REGULAR SESSION</font></div><br clear="all"/><span id="bill_house_num"><div style="float: left; width:50%; font-weight: bold; "><span style="text-transform: uppercase; text-align:left;width:50%;"><b>
                Assembly Bill
              </b></span></div><div style="float:right; width:50%; text-align:right;"><span style="text-transform: uppercase;"><b>No. 2503</b></span></div></span><hr/><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><table style="border-collapse: collapse" cellSpacing="0" align="center" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td id="bill_authors" align="center"><span style="font-weight:bold;">Introduced by Assembly Member Wallis<br/></span></td></tr><tr><td id="bill_intro_date" align="center" class="textcenter"><br/>February 20, 2026</td></tr></tbody></table></div><hr/><br clear="all"/><div id="title"><span style="font-weight:normal;font-size:0.9em;"> An act to amend Section 35179.8 of the Education Code, relating to interscholastic athletic programs. </span></div><br clear="all"/><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><h2>LEGISLATIVE COUNSEL'S DIGEST</h2></div><br/><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0"><span id="subject">AB 2503, as amended, Wallis.
                          California Interscholastic Federation: pupil health: heat illness: guidelines.</span></div><div><span id="digesttext"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Existing law describes the California Interscholastic Federation (CIF) as a voluntary organization that consists of school and school-related personnel with responsibility for administering interscholastic athletic activities in secondary schools, and sets forth the Legislature’s intent regarding the CIF’s implementation of certain policies. Existing law requires the CIF, in consultation with the State Department of Education, to develop guidelines, procedures, and safety standards for the prevention and management of exertional heat illness.<font color="#B30000"><strike> Pursuant to that requirement, the CIF has established Wet Bulb Globe Temperature (WBGT) thresholds for outdoor practices and contests, including, for among other regions, Region Category 3 where the CIF prohibits outdoor activities at WBGT readings exceeding 92 degrees Fahrenheit.</strike></font></div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">This bill would require, on or before July 1, 2027, <font color="#B30000"><strike>the CIF to revise those guidelines for schools located in extreme desert climates within Region Category 3 to (1) instead permit outdoor practices and contests up to a WBGT of 93.5 degrees Fahrenheit if additional safety measures are implemented and (2) define eligibility for those schools based on objective climatic data, as provided. The bill would authorize the threshold in the guidelines for those schools to be raised above a WBGT of 93.5 degrees Fahrenheit based on updated peer-reviewed research, but would prohibit the threshold from being lowered below a WBGT of 93.5 degrees Fahrenheit.</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> and annually thereafter, the CIF to review and update as necessary the guidelines, procedures, and safety standards, with special consideration for regions of the
			 state with higher average temperatures.</i></font></div></span></div><span class="hidden"><h2>Digest Key</h2></span><span id="vote">
      Vote:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">MAJORITY</span>  </span><span id="appropriation">
      Appropriation:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span><span id="fiscalcommittee">
      Fiscal Committee:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span><span id="localprogram">
      Local Program:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span></div><hr/><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Text</h2></span><div id="bill"><div style=" text-transform: uppercase"><h2 style=" text-align: left;">The people of the State of California do enact as follows:</h2><br/></div><div id="s10.5946787631189414"><div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h3 style="font-weight:bold; display:inline;">SECTION 1.</h3> The Legislature finds and declares all of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(a) The California Interscholastic Federation (CIF) has established regional categories based on climate to guide Wet Bulb Globe Temperature (WBGT) thresholds for outdoor practices and contests, with Category 3 regions, including extreme desert areas, currently prohibiting outdoor activities at WBGT readings of 92.1 degrees Fahrenheit or higher.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) In acclimatized desert regions, where pupils and communities routinely experience prolonged high temperatures, the current 92.1 degrees Fahrenheit threshold is overly restrictive and
				forces practices into late evening hours.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(c) Late-evening practices disrupt family time, create logistical challenges for transportation and supervision, exhaust pupil-athletes, and contribute to decreased participation in youth sports at a critical time when maintaining engagement in physical activity is essential for health and well-being.</div><font color="#B30000"><strike><p style="display:inline;"><s>(d)<span class="EnSpace"/>Establishing a specialized regional category for extreme desert climates that would allow outdoor practices with enhanced safety protocols when the WBGT is up to 93.5 degrees Fahrenheit will better balance pupil health protections with practical considerations while remaining grounded in evidence-based heat illness prevention standards.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div></strike></font></div></div><div id="s20.4665678238028128"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0" class="ActionLine"><h3 style="font-weight:bold; display:inline;">SEC. 2.</h3> Section 35179.8 of the Education Code is amended to read:</div><div><div id="id_675B0737-D18B-43AC-A2BE-AA832A250B48"><div><p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;">35179.8.</h6> (a) <font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>(1)</i></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> </i></font>In order to better protect student athletes participating in athletics,<font color="#B30000"><strike> no later than</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> on or before</i></font> July 1, 2024, the California Interscholastic Federation, in consultation with the department, shall develop guidelines, procedures, and safety standards for the prevention and management of exertional heat illness.</div><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) On or before July 1, 2027, and annually thereafter, the California Interscholastic Federation shall review and update as necessary the guidelines, procedures, and safety standards for the prevention and management of exertional heat illness, with special consideration for regions of the state with higher average temperatures.</div></i></font><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) Guidelines developed pursuant to subdivision (a) shall identify the environmental conditions at which a school shall limit and prohibit practice and play. These guidelines shall include information regarding the accurate measurement of environmental heat stress at the site of the athletic activity, including the use of Wet Bulb Globe Temperature (WBGT) to determine ambient temperature, relative humidity, wind speed, and solar radiation from the sun, including sun
						angle and cloud cover.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(c) Guidelines developed pursuant to subdivision (a) shall identify the environmental conditions at which a school shall have a method to institute whole-body cooling to treat a student athlete with exertional heat illness, especially heat stroke, that is easily accessible at all practice and contest venues.</div><font color="#B30000"><strike><p style="display:inline;"><s>(d)<span class="EnSpace"/>The California Interscholastic Federation shall, on or
				  before July 1, 2027, revise the guidelines developed pursuant to subdivision (a) for schools located in extreme desert climates within Region Category 3, characterized by prolonged periods of high ambient temperatures and acclimatized populations, consistent with all of the following:</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;"> (1)<span class="EnSpace"/>The guidelines shall permit outdoor practices and contests for those schools up to a WBGT of 93.5 degrees Fahrenheit if additional safety measures are implemented. The additional safety measures shall include, but not be limited to, all of the following:</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><s><p style="margin-left: 2.5em;">(A)<span class="EnSpace"/>Mandatory hydration breaks every 15 minutes.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><s><p style="margin-left: 2.5em;">(B)<span class="EnSpace"/>Reduced practice intensity and duration.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><s><p style="margin-left: 2.5em;">(C)<span class="EnSpace"/>Onsite monitoring by trained personnel for signs of heat illness.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><s><p style="margin-left: 2.5em;">(D)<span class="EnSpace"/>Enhanced heat acclimatization protocols.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><s><p style="margin-left: 2.5em;">(E)<span class="EnSpace"/>Availability of shaded rest areas and cooling measures.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;">(2)<span class="EnSpace"/>The guidelines shall define eligibility for those schools based on objective climatic data, such as average summer WBGT readings, historical temperature patterns, or other scientifically validated criteria.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><s><p style="margin-left: 1em;">(3)<span class="EnSpace"/>The threshold in the guidelines for those schools may be raised above a WBGT of 93.5 degrees Fahrenheit based on updated peer-reviewed research, but it shall not be lowered below a WBGT of 93.5 degrees Fahrenheit.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div></strike></font></p></div></div></div></div></div></div></body></html>
